00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:55.955
And then there's a charge
row and a current that's CJ.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:06.110
So how we get the wave equation
from that is quite simple.

00:03:06.110 --> 00:03:10.270
It's just a case of doing a
bit of vector manipulation.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:20.230
Curl E, you can see,
is minus the Bdt

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:21.890
from the Maxwell's equations.

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:25.060
So if you take the curl
of both sides of that,

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:27.580
you get this equation.

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:33.430
And curl B is another of
the Maxwell's equations,

00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:37.480
so you can substitute in
from the Maxwell's equation

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:42.670
into this one, and then
you'll get another equation.

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:46.900
What you get after that George
hasn't actually written here,

00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:49.660
but basically, what
you'd obviously get then,

00:03:49.660 --> 00:03:54.100
this is curl of this, so it's
going to be curl of curl.

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:00.540
So this is what you actually
end up with, is curl, curl,

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:04.260
curl E is going to be--

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:06.620
and then the other term
is going to be something--

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:13.790
a second derivative in the E. So
actually, that equation, maybe

00:04:13.790 --> 00:04:15.530
I'll write it down.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.019
It's not actually written
there, but after you've just

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:21.050
done that substitution,
you'll get something

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:24.250
like-- is this thing
working, or-- yeah, it is.

00:04:24.250 --> 00:04:34.820
You'd get something like
curl of curl E. There we are.

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:36.210
Now you can see it.

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:42.590
A lot of people right cross
product like that, as a little,

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:49.380
sort of upside down V.
Curl curl E plus mu naught

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:57.080
epsilon naught, d2, edt
squared equals naught,

00:04:57.080 --> 00:04:59.720
is I think what you
get after you've just

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:01.940
substituted that in there.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:07.490
And then finally--
so this is-- this

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:10.250
has still got this thing,
curl of curl E, which

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:12.290
is quite complicated
if you try and work out

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:16.400
what that is in spherical
polars or something,

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:19.790
especially if you're expressing
E as something which is

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:22.130
spatially varying or whatever.

00:05:22.130 --> 00:05:24.920
This could be quite
a complicated thing

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:27.140
to have to work out.

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:32.210
But anyway, but the-- you can
get it into a slightly more

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:34.430
usable form--

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.020
often we do this--

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:39.890
by using this
identity, curl curl E

00:05:39.890 --> 00:05:46.760
is equal to grad of div
E minus Del squared E.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:49.400
It calls it here an identity.

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:52.460
Really, it's actually
the definition

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:54.620
of what this thing means.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:58.685
And this is not obvious,
what this means, actually.

00:06:01.730 --> 00:06:04.940
But these other
things, OK, they're

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:06.800
well defined, what they mean.

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:09.530
This thing is
actually just what it

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:13.880
says in Cartesian
coordinates, so you

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:21.050
know you've got Del is
equal to ddx in the I

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:25.730
direction, plus ddy
in the J direction,

00:06:25.730 --> 00:06:28.440
plus dd zed in the K direction.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:32.130
So Del squared is going
to be this dot this,

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:38.360
which is going to be d2 Del
squared equals d2, dx squared,

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:42.600
plus d2, dy squared,
plus d2, d zed squared.

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:46.250
And you'll notice that
that's exactly the same form

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:48.880
as the normal Laplacian, right?

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:51.820
So the lower
Laplacian you've had

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:55.000
before, Del squared of a
scalar, but this is different,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.990
because this is Del
squared of a vector.

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:03.070
So what we're saying is that,
for Cartesian coordinates,

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:06.610
if we define Del squared
of a vector by this thing,

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:10.090
we find that it's got
exactly the same form

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:11.830
as Del squared of a scalar.

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:13.480
Now, that doesn't
actually work with

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:16.840
any other coordinate system,
so that's a bit of a warning.

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:21.760
If you go into sphericals
or cylindrical coordinates,

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:26.530
you'll find that this
Del squared of a vector

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:29.200
is not the same as
Del squared that you

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:30.190
would use for a scalar.

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:36.170
But nevertheless, let's do that.

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:39.320
We stick in this as being that.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.100
And then we look
at this term here,

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:46.880
and mostly, we're going to be
interested in, for example,

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:50.630
regions where
there's no charges.

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:54.610
And very often,
also, we're going

00:07:54.610 --> 00:07:57.450
to be interested
in isotropic media.

00:07:57.450 --> 00:08:03.950
If these things are true, you
know that div D equals row,

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:10.070
so Div d is equal to naught
if there's no charges, which

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:13.790
means that Div E is equal to
naught if there's no charges,

00:08:13.790 --> 00:08:16.130
and it's also isotropic.

00:08:16.130 --> 00:08:20.000
So I'm saying this
all out in length

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.310
because you have to be very
careful about this, sometimes.

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:29.180
Div E equals naught is only
true if you've got no charges,

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:31.620
and it's an isotropic medium.

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:36.140
So if you've got, for example,
let's say a diffraction

00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:41.120
grating, where you've got some
variations in permittivity,

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:44.360
then in general, you can't
actually assume this,

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:47.720
because epsilon is changing.

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:49.770
And therefore, with
div D equals naught,

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:52.520
div epsilon doesn't
equal naught.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:58.370
But if you're in free space or
some constant isotopic medium,

00:08:58.370 --> 00:08:59.520
this is true.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:02.600
So this term goes,
and so this is just

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:04.710
equal to minus Del squared.

00:09:04.710 --> 00:09:07.460
And so you can see then,
this Dell squared then

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:11.270
is just replaced by this, and
we got a sign change there.

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:13.880
So this is the final expression.

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:15.950
And you'll notice then
that this is exactly

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.790
the same form as the
normal wave equation

00:09:19.790 --> 00:09:23.660
that we're very used
to in this scalar form,

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:26.550
except that the scalar
is replaced by a vector.

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:29.300
So that's really very nice.

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:39.480
Yeah, so comparing with
that wave equation,

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:42.330
this is the normal wave
equation we've had,

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:45.750
the scalar wave equation before,
and you can see then they're

00:09:45.750 --> 00:09:48.420
exactly the same, except
that the scalar is

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:50.250
replaced by a vector.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:52.980
And the one over
c squared, where

00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:55.470
c is the velocity
of the wave, is

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.900
replaced by this thing,
so we can say then

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:03.030
that 1 over c squared is equal
to mu naught epsilon naught,

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:06.770
and that gives us then c is
1 over the square root of mu

00:10:06.770 --> 00:10:08.910
naught epsilon naught.

00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:12.330
And so here, there are
some figures put in,

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:21.610
and we get the expression for
the speed of light in vacuum.

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:24.360
So that's very neat.

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:26.910
I guess Maxwell must
have been really amazed

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:27.855
when he did this sum.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:33.690
You don't know, of course, the
actual history of the thing,

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:36.840
but he played around with
these equations, didn't he?

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:41.040
And he came up with this
form which looked nicely

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:42.810
symmetrical to him.

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:46.290
And then he comes out with
an expression, comes out

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:49.800
with a value, for the speed
of light that it predicts,

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:52.260
which is what they
already knew was true.

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:55.500
So he must have felt
really as though he

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:58.350
was going to get the
Nobel Prize or something.

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:00.090
But probably, I
don't know-- maybe

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:06.060
it was before the Nobel
Prize, so quite interesting.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.670
And actually, Naveen
was telling me

00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:13.200
that he'd been looking at the
original paper by Maxwell.

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:17.250
Maxwell's equations, if you look
in the original, are horrible,

00:11:17.250 --> 00:11:19.860
because he doesn't--

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:23.640
this terminology for vectors
wasn't invented then.

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:26.640
So it's done all in
terms of components,

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:28.980
horribly complicated.

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:31.980
And I think Naveen
said it was the--

00:11:31.980 --> 00:11:37.290
Heaviside who actually really
derived the Maxwell's equations

00:11:37.290 --> 00:11:43.410
in the form that we know
and love so well nowadays.

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:46.925
Heaviside you might remember,
he's famous for a few things,

00:11:46.925 --> 00:11:48.300
but one of them
is a thing called

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:53.150
the Heaviside function, which
is basically a step function.

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:55.820
And the other thing is
the Heaviside layer,

00:11:55.820 --> 00:12:02.150
which is an ionic
layer in the ionosphere

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:04.160
that he reflects
radio waves from.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:14.880
OK, so that's all
about free space.

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:18.690
So how can we now
deal with matter?

00:12:18.690 --> 00:12:21.320
Well, it turns out actually
there's lots of different ways

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:23.360
you can deal with--

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:26.870
lots of levels you can
deal with propagation

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:30.710
of electromagnetic
waves in matter.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:34.370
You can, for example,
treat it really

00:12:34.370 --> 00:12:36.740
from a proper atomic
point of view.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:40.160
You can think of the
material being made up

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:48.500
of atoms which have got nuclei
and electrons clouds and so on.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:51.290
Or you can think of
it in terms of matter

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:53.510
just being like an
isotropic material, where

00:12:53.510 --> 00:12:56.460
you don't really go into
the microscopic view of it,

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:01.270
but just think of it
in a macroscopic way.

00:13:01.270 --> 00:13:05.880
And actually, to some degree,
I think that, very often,

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:10.270
the second of those is just as
well, because normally, we're

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:14.800
not really interested in the
actual atomic nature of where

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.540
these properties come from.

00:13:16.540 --> 00:13:20.020
But this is going back to how
you can think of it, really,

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:22.060
in terms of atoms.

00:13:22.060 --> 00:13:23.770
So as you know,
atoms are made up

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:28.010
of a nucleus with
an electron cloud.

00:13:28.010 --> 00:13:31.300
And the nucleus is
relatively fixed,

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:35.830
of course, because it's
heavy, but the electron cloud,

00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:38.260
because the electrons
are much lighter,

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:43.300
can be moved around by
the field that's supplied.

00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:46.520
So you get the distortion
of the electron cloud.

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:48.940
So this is what this
is showing here.

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:53.180
It's showing here
the nucleus here,

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:55.840
which is pretty well fixed,
because it's so heavy.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.900
And then this
electron cloud, you

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:01.180
can think of it like being
joined to the nucleus

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:02.980
by a lot of springs.

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:05.730
And then the electrostatic--

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:09.580
the forces on that
electric cloud

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:13.010
caused by the electric field
will tend to, for example,

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:17.500
displace the electron cloud
relative to the nucleus.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.870
So it gets sort of distorted.

00:14:19.870 --> 00:14:25.960
And the way that's described is
in terms of a property called

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:29.200
the polarization then.

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:31.000
So this is showing how--

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.060
you can see that if you
move the negative charges

00:14:34.060 --> 00:14:36.280
relative to the
positive charges,

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:38.680
you'll set up a sort
of dipole moment.

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:41.620
Separate the charges, you've
got a plus and a minus.

00:14:41.620 --> 00:14:45.430
They're separated in distance,
so that acts like a dipole.

00:14:45.430 --> 00:14:47.590
So that acts like a--

00:14:47.590 --> 00:14:50.020
gives you a dipole
moment, and then

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:53.170
if you sum over all
those dipole moments,

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:55.530
you'll get the
total polarization

00:14:55.530 --> 00:14:57.550
effects of applying that field.

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:08.450
So what that does then is
introduces these charge

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:17.450
variations, which distort
the charge that you really

00:15:17.450 --> 00:15:21.120
have there, which is caused
by the bound charges.

00:15:21.120 --> 00:15:23.600
So this is what we get.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.240
You can say that
div D equals row,

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:33.440
so div E is equal to row over
epsilon naught, assuming the--

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:35.450
yeah, well, this is--
epsilon naught, of course,

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:37.060
is really a constant.

00:15:37.060 --> 00:15:43.250
And we are breaking this up into
it's bound-and-free components,

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:48.620
and we're saying
that the free part--

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:51.870
we've got something wrong
with this again, haven't we?

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:53.260
Sorry, that should say--

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:55.040
that should say free
there, shouldn't it?

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:55.800
Yeah.

00:15:55.800 --> 00:16:01.360
The free part and the
bound part is this part,

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:03.880
and so this is it,
the final result then.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:06.760
We can now take the epsilon
naught the other side,

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:08.920
take this the other
side, and we get

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:17.170
the div of epsilon naught E plus
P is equal to the free charges,

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:17.770
right?

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:21.290
And then this thing
in brackets here

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:26.420
is what we call D, the
displacement in the medium.

00:16:26.420 --> 00:16:28.660
So it's like if you've
got this medium,

