00:31:54.498 --> 00:31:56.290
So perhaps, I'll say
a bit more about that.

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:01.330
Well, this first
part is all right.

00:32:01.330 --> 00:32:05.410
We've got curl E is minus db dt.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:08.800
And we know that the
time dependence is this e

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:10.360
to the minus i omega t.

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:14.750
So ddt of e to the minus i
omega t is very straightforward.

00:32:14.750 --> 00:32:20.040
That's just-- the minus i
omega comes out the front.

00:32:20.040 --> 00:32:21.070
So that's what we get.

00:32:24.140 --> 00:32:35.520
Curl e is equal to minus db,
dt, is equal to i omega b.

00:32:35.520 --> 00:32:38.910
And so we can say then
that b is equal to minus

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:44.060
i over omega curl e, all right?

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:50.360
So if we know what e is, we can
work out what b is from that.

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:55.730
And so we take e as being
this thing, all right?

00:32:55.730 --> 00:32:59.330
So in general, this
might not be traveling

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:02.720
in the x direction or any
other particular direction.

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:07.650
It might be just pointing
in some direction in space.

00:33:07.650 --> 00:33:09.860
So really, I guess,
you ought to do it

00:33:09.860 --> 00:33:12.620
for that general
case, which means

00:33:12.620 --> 00:33:14.330
that effectively
what you've got to do

00:33:14.330 --> 00:33:20.650
is to work out what
curl of the e is.

00:33:20.650 --> 00:33:26.800
And e is, effectively, as you
can see, a scalar quantity.

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:28.930
Well, let's forget about
the time dependence.

00:33:28.930 --> 00:33:31.550
We're only looking
at the space now.

00:33:31.550 --> 00:33:34.900
There's this scalar
quantity here.

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:37.010
Time is a constant vector.

00:33:37.010 --> 00:33:41.200
So we then have to use another
of our identities, which

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:45.490
is the curl of a
scalar times a vector.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:49.960
So let's write it like that.

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:53.740
And you might remember that that
is equal to-- and I had to look

00:33:53.740 --> 00:33:56.780
it up because I never
know these things--

00:33:56.780 --> 00:34:06.890
5 times curl a plus grad
phi across a, all right?

00:34:06.890 --> 00:34:11.250
So that is a general
vector identity

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:14.820
which allows you to work out
the curl of this product of two

00:34:14.820 --> 00:34:16.010
things.

00:34:16.010 --> 00:34:19.050
And in our case,
this is a plane wave.

00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:23.739
So this direction of the
e vector is constant.

00:34:23.739 --> 00:34:27.210
So our a is a constant.

00:34:27.210 --> 00:34:30.840
So curl of a is going to
be 0 because it's constant.

00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:32.400
So that goes.

00:34:32.400 --> 00:34:39.090
And we're then left with
the curl of phi times a

00:34:39.090 --> 00:34:41.449
is grad phi cross a.

00:34:41.449 --> 00:34:49.830
And phi is equal to-- phi
equals e to the i k dot r.

00:34:49.830 --> 00:34:55.770
And a is equal to this direction
of the e vector, all right?

00:34:55.770 --> 00:35:00.310
So if phi equals e
to the i k dot r,

00:35:00.310 --> 00:35:07.570
then grad phi is equal to
ik times e to the i k dot r.

00:35:07.570 --> 00:35:10.520
And so we stick that into here.

00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:14.260
And after we've done that,
we can derive this expression

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:14.760
here.

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:19.620
We find that finally
the magnetic vector

00:35:19.620 --> 00:35:22.470
is equal to the cross
products of these two.

00:35:22.470 --> 00:35:24.600
So that's why, of course,
all these three things

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:29.740
have to be right angles
to each other, all right?

00:35:29.740 --> 00:35:32.340
So the next thing,
this is a picture of it

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:34.670
moving along then.

00:35:34.670 --> 00:35:39.510
And we'll stress, very
strongly, something.

00:35:39.510 --> 00:35:45.090
And that is that these two, the
electric and magnetic field,

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.680
are in phase with each other.

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:51.060
I don't know what it
is, but I've often

00:35:51.060 --> 00:35:54.780
found that students don't
seem to pick this up.

00:35:54.780 --> 00:35:57.180
And they come up with
these funny ideas

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.120
about them being in quadrature.

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:02.070
And I think they get it mixed
up with some other things.

00:36:02.070 --> 00:36:06.990
But for a plane polarized
wave, the electric field

00:36:06.990 --> 00:36:08.730
and the magnetic
field, you can see,

00:36:08.730 --> 00:36:10.110
are in phase with each other.

00:36:10.110 --> 00:36:13.890
When the e is a maximum,
the b is a maximum.

00:36:13.890 --> 00:36:16.950
And then they will
have this wave form.

00:36:16.950 --> 00:36:22.140
Here this is showing the wave
as a function of distance.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:26.070
This is like a snapshot of what
happens at a particular time.

00:36:26.070 --> 00:36:29.940
But you could equally well get
a very similar sort of thing

00:36:29.940 --> 00:36:32.760
by looking at a
particular position

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:35.130
and seeing how it
changes with time.

00:36:35.130 --> 00:36:37.920
You'd also get sine
waves like this.

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:41.490
And you would also
see that these two,

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:43.950
the electric and
magnetic fields,

00:36:43.950 --> 00:36:48.670
have to be in phase with each
other for that case, too.

00:36:48.670 --> 00:36:49.170
OK?

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:52.800
This is expressing--
showing you, again,

00:36:52.800 --> 00:36:57.090
this right-hand rule
or whatever it is for--

00:36:57.090 --> 00:36:59.040
I don't know how
you do these things.

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:01.320
But anyway, I always like the--

00:37:01.320 --> 00:37:04.120
I can never do these, partly
because I'm left-handed,

00:37:04.120 --> 00:37:04.890
I think.

00:37:04.890 --> 00:37:06.520
It ruins things.

00:37:06.520 --> 00:37:10.650
But this corkscrew
rule is the one

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:12.210
that I always know that one.

00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.160
And my students will
know it's because I'm

00:37:14.160 --> 00:37:16.974
very handy with a corkscrew.

00:37:16.974 --> 00:37:18.890
[LAUGHS]

00:37:18.890 --> 00:37:22.970
So this is showing, then, how
this electric field varies

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:26.360
with space, the fixed time.

00:37:26.360 --> 00:37:31.490
And the distance, then,
between these maxima

00:37:31.490 --> 00:37:35.330
in the electric field is
the wavelength, all right?

00:37:35.330 --> 00:37:38.270
So this is going to propagate.

00:37:38.270 --> 00:37:40.100
It's a traveling wave.

00:37:40.100 --> 00:37:43.700
So this structure moves
bodily, doesn't it,

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:48.590
in time along this
direction of propagation.

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:55.460
Ah, and now we get
onto this thing

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:58.550
that I was talking with George
about on the way, the Poynting

00:37:58.550 --> 00:37:59.990
vector.

00:37:59.990 --> 00:38:05.620
And I don't think you actually
really sort of prove it,

00:38:05.620 --> 00:38:06.940
do you, what it really does.

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:13.720
But basically the Poynting
vector, it turns out,

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:17.170
is a measure of the energy flow.

00:38:17.170 --> 00:38:19.780
So it's a way of looking
at the energy that's

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:21.790
carried by a wave.

00:38:21.790 --> 00:38:25.570
And this is the
definition of it.

00:38:25.570 --> 00:38:29.800
So s is equal to 1
over mu 0, e cross b.

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:31.860
Actually, you can see b equals--

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.930
actually, I think this should
really be mu, shouldn't it,

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:39.550
not mu 0, really, if it
was in a general medium.

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:42.250
And b equals mu h, of course.

00:38:42.250 --> 00:38:46.110
So this is really cross h.

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:52.780
So that's the way it's sometimes
derived, sometimes defined.

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:56.950
But anyway, but if you're
in free space, then

00:38:56.950 --> 00:38:59.530
you can write it with
mu 0 here like that.

00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:06.550
And then, using our expression
for the velocity of light,

00:39:06.550 --> 00:39:08.330
then we can write it like this.

00:39:08.330 --> 00:39:13.570
But I think this is also
true for free space only.

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:15.970
I think that's right.

00:39:15.970 --> 00:39:19.440
Presumably this is
from Hecht again.

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:24.520
OK, so this is what
our waves look like.

00:39:24.520 --> 00:39:30.460
Each of electric and magnetic
fields is a cosine-type wave.

00:39:30.460 --> 00:39:33.550
So this represents,
then, a wave which

00:39:33.550 --> 00:39:38.520
is moving in this
direction, all right?

00:39:38.520 --> 00:39:42.610
So this thing in here basically
is the phase, isn't it?

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:45.280
You got cos of a phase term.

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:48.930
So you can see that
as omega t varies,

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:50.940
so the shape of
the wave is going

00:39:50.940 --> 00:39:54.420
to sort of move in a
particular direction.

00:39:54.420 --> 00:39:57.880
And you'll notice that--
oh, this is a vector.

00:39:57.880 --> 00:40:00.480
This is a vector, but
this is a constant vector.

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:03.600
So this is a vector
which tells you

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:08.550
the amplitude of that wave
in magnitude and direction.

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:11.190
And you'll notice
that these cosine bits

00:40:11.190 --> 00:40:14.060
are exactly the same.

00:40:14.060 --> 00:40:16.850
That's because, as we
said, the e and the b

00:40:16.850 --> 00:40:19.510
are in phase with each other.

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:21.830
And so all that's very simple.

00:40:21.830 --> 00:40:25.020
And so what we can say
is that if we represent

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:28.240
the fields like this,
we can say, according

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:30.640
to our definition of
the Poynting vector,

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:32.900
we can write it like this.

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:38.020
And so we end up, then, cos
times cos is cos squared.

00:40:38.020 --> 00:40:45.580
So notice that, although cos
of course can go negative,

00:40:45.580 --> 00:40:46.660
it's periodic, isn't it?

00:40:46.660 --> 00:40:50.830
So it's negative half as
long as it's positive.

00:40:50.830 --> 00:40:53.780
Cos squared is always positive.

00:40:53.780 --> 00:40:57.610
So the way this is defined,
the Poynting vector

00:40:57.610 --> 00:41:00.320
is always going in
the same direction.

00:41:00.320 --> 00:41:03.560
It's always, when
you've got a plane wave,

00:41:03.560 --> 00:41:06.400
the energy is going in the
direction of the direction

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:07.720
of propagation of the wave.

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:20.330
And OK, so this shows
us how we get all this.

00:41:23.330 --> 00:41:27.570
Sorry, let me-- this shows us--

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:28.350
can I go back?

00:41:28.350 --> 00:41:30.350
Aw, yeah.

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:32.830
Oh, I've gone back too far now.

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:34.690
Here we are.

00:41:34.690 --> 00:41:38.290
This shows us how this
Poynting vector varies

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:40.120
in space and time, all right?

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:45.730
So this Poynting vector has also
got a sort of wave-type nature.

00:41:45.730 --> 00:41:47.410
But normally what
we're interested in

00:41:47.410 --> 00:41:50.920
is not how it varies
in space and time,

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:54.950
but what the time-averaged form
of that is going to look like.

00:41:54.950 --> 00:41:57.280
And so we can do a
time average of it.

00:42:02.010 --> 00:42:05.810
And so that's what
this thing here is.

00:42:05.810 --> 00:42:12.090
This s with the lines on either
side is the time average of s.

00:42:12.090 --> 00:42:20.490
And so we've got b is
k times e over omega.

00:42:20.490 --> 00:42:24.620
And so therefore we've
got here e cross b.

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:26.150
And we know what b is.

00:42:26.150 --> 00:42:27.680
So we can put that in.

00:42:27.680 --> 00:42:30.086
And we're going to
get now e squared.

00:42:30.086 --> 00:42:32.820
All right, so
finally what we get

00:42:32.820 --> 00:42:38.880
is that the Poynting vector
is proportional to the time

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:41.580
average of the
electric field squared.

00:42:41.580 --> 00:42:43.333
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:43.333 --> 00:42:44.250
COLIN SHEPPARD: Sorry?

00:42:44.250 --> 00:42:45.132
AUDIENCE: Let's
take the average.

00:42:45.132 --> 00:42:46.455
We haven't done the average.

00:42:46.455 --> 00:42:48.622
COLIN SHEPPARD: Oh, we
haven't done any average yet.

00:42:48.622 --> 00:42:49.950
Sorry, but this is the modulus.

00:42:49.950 --> 00:42:50.450
So--

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:52.170
AUDIENCE: Anyway [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:52.170 --> 00:42:53.298
COLIN SHEPPARD: It's the--

00:42:53.298 --> 00:42:54.630
AUDIENCE: So right now--

00:42:54.630 --> 00:42:56.440
COLIN SHEPPARD: What
do the two lines mean?

00:42:56.440 --> 00:42:58.946
AUDIENCE: The magnitude
of the vector.

00:42:58.946 --> 00:43:01.154
COLIN SHEPPARD: OK, it's
the magnitude of the vector.

00:43:01.154 --> 00:43:02.363
AUDIENCE: A function of time.

00:43:02.363 --> 00:43:04.470
COLIN SHEPPARD: It's
still a function of time.

00:43:04.470 --> 00:43:08.800
OK, we'll take it as that, yeah.

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:12.980
And yeah, OK.

00:43:16.120 --> 00:43:19.620
And I think, really,
if it's in a medium,

00:43:19.620 --> 00:43:21.400
this is epsilon, not epsilon 0.

00:43:21.400 --> 00:43:22.010
Is that right?

00:43:22.010 --> 00:43:22.507
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:22.507 --> 00:43:23.382
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah.

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:29.830
OK, so now we're going
to do the time averaging.

00:43:29.830 --> 00:43:33.880
So this e, e is a
time-varying quantity.

00:43:33.880 --> 00:43:37.140
e varies with both
space and time.

00:43:37.140 --> 00:43:45.870
And so this is the modular
square of it, of the vector.

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:47.940
So we put that in.

00:43:47.940 --> 00:43:53.655
And we get, then, the s is equal
to something we cos squared.

00:43:53.655 --> 00:43:55.780
So it's not much different
from what we had before.

00:43:58.440 --> 00:44:02.760
OK, and then the next thing we
do is to do the time averaging.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:10.770
So this is something which
is positive but oscillating,

00:44:10.770 --> 00:44:12.270
time-varying.

00:44:12.270 --> 00:44:16.480
And the speed of these
variations is very, very fast.

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:21.600
We've said before the
frequency of light is around 10

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:27.300
to the 15 Hertz, which is
faster than any detector

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:30.640
that we have to measure the
fields directly, all right?

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:33.990
So you can't actually
measure the electric field

00:44:33.990 --> 00:44:39.930
or the power of an optical
wave because the frequency's

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:41.580
so high.

00:44:41.580 --> 00:44:48.120
So a normal detector, like
a photo diode or whatever,

00:44:48.120 --> 00:44:51.180
would be measuring some
time average of this

00:44:51.180 --> 00:44:52.920
because there's no
way it can respond

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:55.150
to this sort of frequency.

00:44:55.150 --> 00:44:58.440
So we do the time average.

00:44:58.440 --> 00:45:02.590
And so this is how we can
do the time average, right?

00:45:02.590 --> 00:45:06.600
The square things mean time
average, the caret signs.

00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:11.040
And the time average, you
integrate this over a long time

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:15.440
and divide by the time
to get the time average.

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:20.140
And so this is called--

00:45:20.140 --> 00:45:22.070
well, usually called intensity.

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:27.110
I think that "intensity" is
now frowned upon by purists.

00:45:27.110 --> 00:45:31.220
And they come up with new
names every now and then.

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:36.770
So "irradiance" is a word
that you often read nowadays

00:45:36.770 --> 00:45:38.460
in the literature.

00:45:38.460 --> 00:45:40.970
And yeah, so here
it's measured in watts

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:47.240
per square meter, which is
obviously a unit of power

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:49.700
density, all right?

00:45:49.700 --> 00:45:52.130
There's one other thing
that's worth mentioning here.

00:45:52.130 --> 00:45:57.200
And that is actually that
normal detectors actually really

00:45:57.200 --> 00:46:00.250
don't measure the
Poynting vector.

00:46:00.250 --> 00:46:04.880
They actually usually measure
the electric energy density.

00:46:04.880 --> 00:46:09.830
And there's a thing called
Poynting's theorem, which,

00:46:09.830 --> 00:46:12.080
if you study
electromagnetism, will

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:16.490
show that the power
flow out of a volume

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:20.090
is equal to the rate of
change of the stored energy.

00:46:20.090 --> 00:46:21.770
And the stored
energy is made up of

00:46:21.770 --> 00:46:23.330
electric and magnetic energy.

00:46:23.330 --> 00:46:25.760
So all these things are related.

00:46:25.760 --> 00:46:31.100
And it turns out that for all
practical purposes normally

00:46:31.100 --> 00:46:35.270
it doesn't really matter whether
you're measuring the Poynting

00:46:35.270 --> 00:46:40.700
vector or the electric
energy density or whatever.

00:46:40.700 --> 00:46:43.160
It's going to give the
same sort of answer.

00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:46.100
But there are cases where
you have to be careful.

00:46:50.070 --> 00:46:53.850
OK, and then finally we've got
to do this time average of cos

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:55.450
squared.

00:46:55.450 --> 00:47:00.270
And the time average of
cos squared is just a half.

00:47:00.270 --> 00:47:02.660
You remember how you do that?

00:47:02.660 --> 00:47:06.900
Cos squared, you go
into double angles.

00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:09.300
And then you get a
cosine that cancels out.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:11.760
And you're just left
with the constant bit.

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:14.970
And then, finally then,
you put that half in.

00:47:14.970 --> 00:47:18.090
And we've now got an
expression for the intensity,

00:47:18.090 --> 00:47:23.100
defined as being the time
average of the Poynting vector

00:47:23.100 --> 00:47:30.080
as being equal to the amplitude
of the electric field squared,

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:34.520
multiplied by some
constant, which,

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:37.680
in probably 99 cases out
of 100, we don't even

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:39.840
bother to even think
what that constant

00:47:39.840 --> 00:47:43.390
is, let alone thinking of
whether there's a half there.

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:46.890
So you'll see loads
of books or papers

00:47:46.890 --> 00:47:48.840
where they just say
that the intensity is

00:47:48.840 --> 00:47:53.420
equal to e squared, which is
strictly not true, I guess,

00:47:53.420 --> 00:47:54.650
but people do say.

00:47:58.690 --> 00:48:00.400
So how are we going?

00:48:00.400 --> 00:48:06.570
We got one hour, yeah.

00:48:06.570 --> 00:48:11.490
OK, so that's how you
can calculate the power

00:48:11.490 --> 00:48:16.060
flow for a plane wave.

00:48:16.060 --> 00:48:18.470
I guess the method
is not only going

00:48:18.470 --> 00:48:19.760
to be true for plane waves.

00:48:19.760 --> 00:48:23.350
But you can apply it for
other sorts of waves, too.

00:48:23.350 --> 00:48:27.220
But the next thing is you
might think back to what

00:48:27.220 --> 00:48:29.380
we were doing with phases.

00:48:29.380 --> 00:48:31.330
And there are a
few things that are

00:48:31.330 --> 00:48:34.030
important to realize
here, what you can do

00:48:34.030 --> 00:48:37.280
and what you can't do.

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:39.470
You remember this is what
we said from our phases.

00:48:39.470 --> 00:48:44.990
We said that what we actually
measure in the real world

00:48:44.990 --> 00:48:46.730
is a wave that's like this.

00:48:46.730 --> 00:48:52.030
It's a cosine dependence
in space and time.

00:48:52.030 --> 00:48:57.250
And we say that we use
this complex representative

00:48:57.250 --> 00:49:00.460
where we say that
this is the real part

00:49:00.460 --> 00:49:03.940
of some complex exponential.

00:49:03.940 --> 00:49:06.370
And if you remember, the
reason for doing that

00:49:06.370 --> 00:49:08.560
is that these
complex exponentials

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:11.770
are much easier to manipulate.

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:15.160
It means that you don't have to
remember all those horrible cos

00:49:15.160 --> 00:49:17.900
of a plus b things and so on.

00:49:17.900 --> 00:49:23.220
So it's much easier to do
the algebra using these.

00:49:23.220 --> 00:49:27.100
So what you do normally,
as you remember,

00:49:27.100 --> 00:49:32.700
is you do all your algebra
with each of the i-somethings.

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:35.910
And then right at the
very end normally,

00:49:35.910 --> 00:49:39.420
you find the real
part to find what

00:49:39.420 --> 00:49:45.060
the real field is in real
space, as we're used to.

00:49:45.060 --> 00:49:48.990
But here, now you've got to
be very careful because you

00:49:48.990 --> 00:49:53.480
saw that the Poynting vector
actually was cos squared,

00:49:53.480 --> 00:49:54.120
all right?

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:57.450
So this is a nonlinear.

00:49:57.450 --> 00:50:01.170
We performed a
nonlinear operation.

00:50:01.170 --> 00:50:04.050
And if you do
nonlinear operations,

00:50:04.050 --> 00:50:06.300
the same would be true
for nonlinear optics,

00:50:06.300 --> 00:50:07.350
as well, actually.

00:50:07.350 --> 00:50:11.310
You can't do it in
this complex notation

00:50:11.310 --> 00:50:13.830
directly because you just
get the wrong answer.

00:50:13.830 --> 00:50:20.400
If you squared this, you get
an e to the 2i kz minus 5,

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:23.010
wouldn't you?

00:50:23.010 --> 00:50:25.980
Now the real part of
that is not what we want.

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:35.600
So what you've really got to do
is to work through, I guess--

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:39.120
well, the surest way of doing
it is to work through in terms

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:46.440
of the cosines and so on rather
than to go into e to the i's.

00:50:46.440 --> 00:50:48.600
So this is saying a
bit more about this.

00:50:51.590 --> 00:50:56.010
So what we've got, then, is this
is showing how you can do it

00:50:56.010 --> 00:50:58.530
in terms of the cosines.

00:50:58.530 --> 00:51:02.460
So you can see that,
for example, here we've

00:51:02.460 --> 00:51:05.090
got two fields.

00:51:05.090 --> 00:51:07.870
And let's say that
you see the point is

00:51:07.870 --> 00:51:11.450
that, although the
fields are additive,

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:18.700
the power of those
two waves is not

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:21.400
going to be equal to the sum
of the powers of the two waves,

00:51:21.400 --> 00:51:22.120
all right?

00:51:22.120 --> 00:51:28.000
So we can say that the
e's would add coherently.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.160
And then we can work
out the power flow

00:51:30.160 --> 00:51:32.530
of the sum of these two fields.

00:51:32.530 --> 00:51:35.190
And you can see of course,
expanding this square,

00:51:35.190 --> 00:51:37.750
you're going to have
the power of the two.

00:51:37.750 --> 00:51:42.610
But you're also going
to get this cross term,

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:45.280
the cross product
term, which depends--

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:46.390
you can see here--

00:51:46.390 --> 00:51:48.730
on the relative phase
of the two waves.

00:51:48.730 --> 00:51:50.830
If they're out of
phase by 90 degrees,

00:51:50.830 --> 00:51:53.000
then that will go to 0.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:59.020
But if they're in phase, this
of course is going to be strong.

00:51:59.020 --> 00:52:04.720
And so that's one
way of doing it.

00:52:04.720 --> 00:52:08.630
But in terms of
phases, then, you

00:52:08.630 --> 00:52:10.280
can do it in terms of phases.

00:52:10.280 --> 00:52:13.170
I'm just saying you have to
be careful how you do it.

00:52:13.170 --> 00:52:19.610
And so you have to add the
phases first and then find

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:21.380
the modulus square.

00:52:21.380 --> 00:52:25.130
You can't actually
do the squaring

00:52:25.130 --> 00:52:27.810
and then do the real
power, all right?

00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:30.330
So you add these
two phases together,

00:52:30.330 --> 00:52:33.110
which gives the total field.

00:52:33.110 --> 00:52:36.650
And then the intensity
is going to be

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:38.350
the modulus square of this.

00:52:38.350 --> 00:52:39.500
And you expand it.

00:52:39.500 --> 00:52:43.860
And you can see we've got
exactly the same answer.

00:52:43.860 --> 00:52:46.190
So it doesn't matter
which way you do it,

00:52:46.190 --> 00:52:48.470
as long as you do it
one of those ways.

00:52:48.470 --> 00:52:52.340
What you don't want to do is
to try squaring the e-to-the-i

00:52:52.340 --> 00:52:55.670
things and then taking the
real power because you'll get

00:52:55.670 --> 00:52:57.700
something different then.

00:52:57.700 --> 00:53:00.700
And that is the very last slide.

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:03.250
And that is dead on time.

00:53:06.360 --> 00:53:08.300
So, well, whoa,
we've got a couple

00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:09.550
of minutes for some questions.

00:53:09.550 --> 00:53:11.850
So any questions?

00:53:11.850 --> 00:53:13.460
Yes, Sharon?

00:53:13.460 --> 00:53:14.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:19.340
Hello?

00:53:19.340 --> 00:53:21.820
I'm quite curious about
the Poynting vector.

00:53:21.820 --> 00:53:24.200
And you mentioned that
it's actually a cross term,

00:53:24.200 --> 00:53:26.880
and it's similar like
propagation and direction,

00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:28.640
like where the energy flows.

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:32.900
But what about the peculiar
case in evanescent waves?

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:36.042
Does it mean the energy
is not propagating there?

00:53:36.042 --> 00:53:37.250
COLIN SHEPPARD: Oh, oh, dear.

00:53:37.250 --> 00:53:38.510
Oh, yes.

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:41.810
Evanescent waves, you're
getting onto something

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:42.880
really controversial--

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:43.640
AUDIENCE: No, I'm thinking--

00:53:43.640 --> 00:53:44.960
COLIN SHEPPARD:
--here, I think--

00:53:44.960 --> 00:53:45.470
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHS]

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:46.040
COLIN SHEPPARD: --actually.

00:53:46.040 --> 00:53:47.852
AUDIENCE: Well, where
has the energy gone then?

00:53:47.852 --> 00:53:48.769
COLIN SHEPPARD: Sorry?

00:53:48.769 --> 00:53:50.810
AUDIENCE: I mean, if
the Poynting vector is

00:53:50.810 --> 00:53:52.880
the direction of
the energy flow,

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:55.830
then it seems like there's
no propagation in energy

00:53:55.830 --> 00:53:57.935
in the evanescent wave then--

00:53:57.935 --> 00:53:59.450
COLIN SHEPPARD:
Well, it is normally

00:53:59.450 --> 00:54:02.310
said that there is
no energy propagation

00:54:02.310 --> 00:54:03.490
in an evanescent wave.

00:54:03.490 --> 00:54:06.790
But you know, in
a way, there is.

00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:10.280
There's sort of transverse
propagation of energy.

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:14.420
But there's no
energy flow across--

00:54:14.420 --> 00:54:17.390
if you're doing total
internal reflection

00:54:17.390 --> 00:54:19.460
and you're looking
at the steady state,

00:54:19.460 --> 00:54:22.310
there's no energy flow
across the boundary,

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:24.300
I think is true to say.

00:54:24.300 --> 00:54:27.350
Is that true, or--

00:54:27.350 --> 00:54:28.100
yeah, this is--

00:54:28.100 --> 00:54:28.340
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes.

00:54:28.340 --> 00:54:30.673
COLIN SHEPPARD: --getting a
bit controversial, isn't it?

00:54:30.673 --> 00:54:32.650
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yes, you can--

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:33.950
if you have the interface--

00:54:33.950 --> 00:54:35.700
I don't know if anyone
can see, but if you

00:54:35.700 --> 00:54:39.740
have the interface of the TAR,
if you compute the Poynting

00:54:39.740 --> 00:54:42.800
vector in the vertical
direction, those have to be 0.

00:54:42.800 --> 00:54:44.140
The time average is 0.

00:54:44.140 --> 00:54:44.360
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, yeah.

00:54:44.360 --> 00:54:46.610
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: So
you don't have energy flow.

00:54:46.610 --> 00:54:48.440
But you do have energy density.

00:54:48.440 --> 00:54:52.160
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, yeah.

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:53.690
And the other
thing is, you know,

00:54:53.690 --> 00:54:56.060
the question of if
you've got-- and this is

00:54:56.060 --> 00:54:57.600
your total internal reflection.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:55:00.230
So here you get this
evanescent wave.

00:55:00.230 --> 00:55:04.130
Now, of course,
all these questions

00:55:04.130 --> 00:55:08.210
of these evanescent
waves and so on, they all

00:55:08.210 --> 00:55:13.760
rely on assuming infinite plane
waves and infinite surfaces

00:55:13.760 --> 00:55:17.180
and things like that, which
of course none of these things

00:55:17.180 --> 00:55:20.670
can really be strictly
true in practice.

00:55:20.670 --> 00:55:23.690
But if we do this,
then we'd expect

00:55:23.690 --> 00:55:25.340
to get something
which is actually

00:55:25.340 --> 00:55:27.420
traveling in this direction.

00:55:27.420 --> 00:55:31.820
And so in some sense,
I think that there

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:36.660
is some sort of energy flow
in the transverse direction.

00:55:36.660 --> 00:55:40.460
But I'm just having a big
argument about this, not

00:55:40.460 --> 00:55:44.090
for this case, but to do
with some other project

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:47.360
we're doing at the
moment where it's

00:55:47.360 --> 00:55:52.130
to do with when
the h vector is 0.

00:55:52.130 --> 00:55:56.097
And so the question is,
is there energy flow?

00:55:56.097 --> 00:55:57.180
Well, I guess there isn't.

00:55:57.180 --> 00:56:00.380
But I think there's
also this question

00:56:00.380 --> 00:56:06.860
of whether Poynting vector
really always means the energy

00:56:06.860 --> 00:56:09.470
flow.

00:56:09.470 --> 00:56:12.200
In fact, I remember having a
conversation with Emil Wolf

00:56:12.200 --> 00:56:14.240
once about this.

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:19.170
And, well, he said, let
me give you an example.

00:56:19.170 --> 00:56:25.520
Imagine you have a DC
planar electric field

00:56:25.520 --> 00:56:31.040
in this direction, and you
have a DC planar magnetic field

00:56:31.040 --> 00:56:32.720
in this direction.

00:56:32.720 --> 00:56:34.580
Is there any energy flow?

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:36.320
No.

00:56:36.320 --> 00:56:39.380
But you can work out
what e cross h is.

00:56:39.380 --> 00:56:44.510
And you know, so I think
that he put this forward

00:56:44.510 --> 00:56:51.800
as an example which makes you
wonder whether it necessarily

00:56:51.800 --> 00:56:54.110
really always means energy flow.

00:56:54.110 --> 00:56:55.820
We were talking
about this in the lab

00:56:55.820 --> 00:56:58.730
today because
people have come up

00:56:58.730 --> 00:57:04.520
with these solutions where, for
example, energy flow sometimes

00:57:04.520 --> 00:57:06.340
does this.

00:57:06.340 --> 00:57:10.030
So you might get the lines of--

00:57:10.030 --> 00:57:14.140
the Poynting vector might
do something like this.

00:57:18.513 --> 00:57:19.930
So here you can
see that there has

00:57:19.930 --> 00:57:24.920
to be some sort of 0 around here
because this is going this way,

00:57:24.920 --> 00:57:27.020
and this is going this way.

00:57:27.020 --> 00:57:30.730
And here you can actually
get these, sort of,

00:57:30.730 --> 00:57:36.730
closed eddies of Poynting vector
that's going round in circles.

00:57:36.730 --> 00:57:39.430
Now, whether this
really represents

00:57:39.430 --> 00:57:42.370
something that's physical
or not, I don't really know.

00:57:42.370 --> 00:57:44.920
You know, in water flow, I
guess you could get this.

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:47.410
There's no reason why
you couldn't get eddies

00:57:47.410 --> 00:57:49.840
of water going in circles.

00:57:49.840 --> 00:57:53.080
But you know, so
this is what you get.

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:54.800
This is what you
get if you've just

00:57:54.800 --> 00:58:00.450
got a very simple example of
a lens focusing the light.

00:58:00.450 --> 00:58:06.530
You get this sort of pattern if
I look at this in some detail.

00:58:06.530 --> 00:58:11.760
You get this sort of
behavior in this region here.

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:15.090
And there've been papers
that have described this.

00:58:15.090 --> 00:58:18.180
But what it really
means in practice--

00:58:18.180 --> 00:58:24.000
well, I guess nothing
really means anything

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:25.770
unless you can measure it.

00:58:25.770 --> 00:58:27.420
So the question
is, can you come up

00:58:27.420 --> 00:58:30.630
with a detector that
measures Poynting vector?

00:58:30.630 --> 00:58:32.130
And I don't know
the answer to that.

00:58:32.130 --> 00:58:36.810
As I said earlier, I think
normally detectors measure

00:58:36.810 --> 00:58:38.670
electric energy density.

00:58:38.670 --> 00:58:42.510
So people have looked at
what happens in this focused

00:58:42.510 --> 00:58:43.920
region of a lens.

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:47.160
And there are various
ways you can look at that.

00:58:47.160 --> 00:58:50.290
People have used
near-field optics,

00:58:50.290 --> 00:58:53.190
you know, a tapered
fiber to look at it.

00:58:53.190 --> 00:58:58.290
Or you can do some sort of
tomography-type experiments

00:58:58.290 --> 00:59:01.860
with a detector that you
rotate and things like that.

00:59:01.860 --> 00:59:07.820
But to actually measure the
Poynting vector, I don't know.

00:59:07.820 --> 00:59:10.500
Right, any questions
from over there?